SECTION 5 — AUDIENCE INTELLIGENCE
who_they_are:

Adults (25–65) who have noticed a visual change to one or more nails — typically discolouration or texture change. They are not medical professionals. They are in the "is this serious?" stage — not yet convinced they need a doctor but worried enough to research. Many have had it for weeks before searching. A second audience segment: those who already know they had fungus and treated it, now checking if it's coming back or if what they're seeing is a recurrence.
what_they_want_from_this_post:

A clear, confident guide to what nail fungus symptoms actually look like at each stage — with enough visual description that they can compare their nail to what's described. They want the answer to: "Do I have nail fungus?" and "Is this bad enough to see a doctor?" They are not looking for treatment options in depth — they want a diagnostic framework.
what_frustrates_them:

Generic symptom lists with no stage progression. Articles that list 7 symptoms without explaining which appear first or how the infection develops. Lack of any guidance on when to self-treat vs see a professional. No help distinguishing fungus from nail psoriasis or from damage caused by nail polish. Embarrassment around the topic leading them to delay — they want a non-judgmental, direct tone.
